i>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They are run by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HMBT)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They developed as a result of the HMBT outreach work in the slums of Mumbai</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','About','','inherit','open','open','','5-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:18:52','2014-02-26 01:18:52','',5,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/5-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(174,1,'2014-02-26 05:08:11','2014-02-26 05:08:11','The HMBT order has relied entirely on receiving outside donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from any parent organization.   The HMBT is registered as an Indian NGO under the secular name Sneha Jewan Kendra which means Love and Life Center.\r\n\r\nOn this page you can see a list of the major current needs at the orphanages.  Your contribution is greatly appreciated.','Give','','inherit','open','open','','11-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 05:08:11','2014-02-26 05:08:11','',11,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/11-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(140,1,'2014-02-26 01:38:02','2014-02-26 01:38:02','<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages are a place for slum and underprivileged children to grow up and get an education.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There are currently two main locations in greater Mumbai, India:  Sahar (Church Pakdi) Slum  and  Merces-Giriz</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They have been in existence for more than 20 years</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They are run by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HMBT)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They developed as a result of the HMBT outreach work in the slums of Mumbai</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n[donate count=2 type=default]','Home','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:38:02','2014-02-26 01:38:02','',13,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/13-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(129,1,'2014-02-26 01:18:31','2014-02-26 01:18:31','<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages are a place for slum and underprivileged children to grow up and get an education.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There are currently two main locations in greater Mumbai, India: Sahar (Church Pakdi) Slum and Merces-Giriz</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They have been in existence for more than 20 years</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They are run by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity (HMBT)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They developed as a result of the HMBT outreach work in the slums of Mumbai</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','About','','inherit','open','open','','5-autosave-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:18:31','2014-02-26 01:18:31','',5,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/5-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(131,1,'2014-02-26 01:20:21','2014-02-26 01:20:21','<p dir=\"ltr\">Sr. Paulette comes from a Christian Indian family from the island of Mauritus.  In her youth she decided to become a nun and came to Calcutta to join Mother Teresa.  For about 20 years she worked with Mother Teresa mainly helping women and children and doing family planning work.  She developed a severe back condition which required hospitalization. She was sent to a Mumbai hospital where she spent several months.  When she emerged from recuperation Mother Teresa urged her to remain in Mumbai in a life of service.  This is how, in 1989,  she became the foundress of a new order of nuns called the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.  Today the order contains about 40 nuns;  about 10 of these are directly working with Sr. Paulette at the orphanages.</p>\r\n&nbsp;','Paulette','','inherit','open','open','','25-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:20:21','2014-02-26 01:20:21','',25,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/25-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(132,1,'2014-02-26 01:21:42','2014-02-26 01:21:42','<p dir=\"ltr\">Sister Eliza comes from a Christian Indian family in Goa.  She came to Mumbai to study Social Work.  She completed college and a M.A. degree in Social Work.  She was very much drawn to helping the abandoned and poor.  During this time, around 1990,  she was introduced to Sr. Paulette and became the first Sister to join the HMBT.  For more than 20 years now she has been a strong pillar to the order.  Today she spends most of her time running the day to day affairs of the Sahar Orphanage.  She also teaches at a nearby school and through this employment brings in financial support to run the orphanage.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/nuns.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-22\" alt=\"nuns\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/nuns-225x300.png\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a>','Eliza','','inherit','open','open','','23-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:21:42','2014-02-26 01:21:42','',23,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/23-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(133,1,'2014-02-26 01:22:15','2014-02-26 01:22:15','','Auto Draft','','trash','open','open','','auto-draft','','','2014-02-26 01:22:27','2014-02-26 01:22:27','',0,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=133',0,'page','',0),(134,1,'2014-02-26 01:22:27','2014-02-26 01:22:27','','Auto Draft','','inherit','open','open','','133-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:22:27','2014-02-26 01:22:27','',133,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/133-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(135,1,'2014-02-26 01:27:19','2014-02-26 01:27:19','','_Amma','','trash','open','open','','_amma','','','2014-02-26 01:27:31','2014-02-26 01:27:31','',0,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=135',0,'page','',0),(136,1,'2014-02-26 01:27:19','2014-02-26 01:27:19','','_Amma','','inherit','open','open','','135-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:27:19','2014-02-26 01:27:19','',135,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/135-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(137,1,'2014-02-26 01:28:58','2014-02-26 01:28:58','<p dir=\"ltr\">Amma is the resident caretaker of the orphans at Sahar.  She is in her 70’s, a widow.  She was shunned by her own family.  This is how she came to  join the family of the HMBT nuns and orphans for whom she has worked tirelessly for the past 15 years.  She is responsible for cooking, feeding, bathing and dressing the kids,  and being a grandmother to all of them.</p>','Amma','','publish','open','closed','','amma','','','2014-03-10 00:45:11','2014-03-10 00:45:11','',7,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=137',2,'page','',0),(138,1,'2014-02-26 01:28:58','2014-02-26 01:28:58','','Amma','','inherit','open','open','','137-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:28:58','2014-02-26 01:28:58','',137,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/137-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(139,1,'2014-02-26 01:30:49','2014-02-26 01:30:49','<p dir=\"ltr\">Amma is the resident caretaker of the orphans at Sahar.  She is in her 70’s, a widow.  She was shunned by her own family and so has joined the family of the HMBT nuns and orphans for whom she has worked tirelessly for the past 15 years.  She is responsible for cooking, feeding, bathing and dressing the kids and being a grandmother to all of them.</p>','Amma','','inherit','open','open','','137-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:30:49','2014-02-26 01:30:49','',137,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/137-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(141,1,'2014-02-26 01:49:04','2014-02-26 01:49:04','<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, and up to recently,  it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is in the Church Pakadi slum).</p>\r\n Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to local social service agencies.  Often,  orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum they got an opportunity to take care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager home (a slum hut).  Upon her death she donated the property to the local church.  The sisters were able to purchase this property from the church to develop a home base.  Also  around that time they received a donation of land at Merces (a suburb of Mumbai) on which they built a convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses for the HMBT order but grew to become orphanages around 1996, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\nOver the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.  They have grown as an order from just 2 nuns to recently about 40 nuns.  About 10 of these are involved with the orphanages and the remainder are doing parish work in other states in India.\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually into becoming girls only orphanages today.  The boys  previously living there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  For practical reasons it was not possible to have co-ed orphanages.  The boys were often disruptive around girls, not having any male residential mentors or father figures.  Also,  it was not possible to maintain separate living quarters for boys and girls.    There is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage.   Over the years the school became more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent and nearby slums.  Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  A typical classroom is about 200 square feet and holds about 30 kids.  The teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable for their families.  The HMBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','publish','open','closed','','history','','','2014-03-10 00:38:30','2014-03-10 00:38:30','',0,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/?page_id=141',1,'page','',0),(142,1,'2014-02-26 01:49:04','2014-02-26 01:49:04','<p dir=\"ltr\">The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is called Church Pakadi).</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to social service agencies.  Often orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses but grew to become orphanages, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Over the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now,  the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For practical reasons they have evolved gradually into their current set up in which they only have girls under their care.  The boys they previously had have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  There is also some turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school for slum children at Sahar.  Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  The children attending this school have no other viable option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable.  The HMBT school offers a low cost English medium education in subjects ranging from science, to math, to crafts, to language.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT</p>','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:49:04','2014-02-26 01:49:04','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(143,1,'2014-02-26 01:54:03','2014-02-26 01:54:03','<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is called Church Pakadi).</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to social service agencies.  Often orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses but grew to become orphanages, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Over the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now,  the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For practical reasons they have evolved gradually into their current set up in which they only have girls under their care.  The boys they previously had have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  There is also some turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school for slum children at Sahar.  Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  The children attending this school have no other viable option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable.  The HMBT school offers a low cost English medium education in subjects ranging from science, to math, to crafts, to language.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT</p>','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-02-26 01:54:03','2014-02-26 01:54:03','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(145,1,'2014-03-10 00:38:11','2014-03-10 00:38:11','<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, and up to recently,  it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is in the Church Pakadi slum).</p>\n Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to local social service agencies.  Often,  orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.\n\nIn the Sahar slum they got an opportunity to take care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager home (a slum hut).  Upon her death she donated the property to the local church.  The sisters were able to purchase this property from the church to develop a home base.  Also  around that time they received a donation of land at Merces (a suburb of Mumbai) on which they built a convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses for the HMBT order but grew to become orphanages around 1996, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\n\nOver the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.  They have grown as an order from just 2 nuns to recently about 40 nuns.  About 10 of these are involved with the orphanages and the remainder are doing parish work in other states in India.\n\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually into becoming girls only orphanages today.  The boys  previously living there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  For practical reasons it was not possible to have co-ed orphanages.  The boys were often disruptive around girls, not having any male residential mentors or father figures.  Also,  it was not possible to maintain separate living quarters for boys and girls.    There is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\n\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage.   Over the years the school became more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent and nearby slums.  Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  A typical classroom is about 200 square feet and holds about 30 kids.  The teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable for their families.  The HMBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts and dance.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-autosave-v1','','','2014-03-10 00:38:11','2014-03-10 00:38:11','',141,'http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/uncategorized/141-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(150,1,'2014-02-26 04:21:32','2014-02-26 04:21:32','<p dir=\"ltr\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and